  "prompt": "How does a hydraulic brake work? Describe in brief",
  "response": "A hydraulic brake system works by using fluid pressure to transmit force from the brake pedal to the brake pads or shoes, which then create friction to slow down or stop a vehicle. Here\u2019s how it works:\n\n1. **Pedal Activation**: When the driver presses the brake pedal, it pushes a piston in the **master cylinder**.\n2. **Fluid Pressure**: The master cylinder compresses **hydraulic fluid** (brake fluid) in the brake lines, creating pressure.\n3. **Force Transmission**: This pressurized fluid travels through the brake lines to the **wheel cylinders** or **brake calipers** at each wheel.\n4. **Brake Engagement**: The pressure forces the pistons in the calipers or wheel cylinders to push the **brake pads** against the **rotor** (in disc brakes) or the **brake shoes** against the **drum** (in drum brakes).\n5. **Friction and Stopping**: The resulting friction slows down or stops the rotation of the wheels.\n\nThe system relies on the incompressibility of the brake fluid to efficiently transfer force, and it is designed to amplify the driver\u2019s input to effectively stop the vehicle. Regular maintenance, such as checking and replacing brake fluid, ensures the system remains effective and safe.",
